    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-05-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-05-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="1495"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1495">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 855.48/259</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The</hi>
                    <gloss type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State</hi>
                    </gloss>
                    <hi rend="italic">to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 7, 1915</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1525. Your 1948, April 16.<note n="1" xml:id="d1495fn1">See footnote 1, <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1036">p. 1036</ref>.</note>
                    From Berlin, for information relief commission:</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>Foreign Secretary replies that, according to investigations of German
                        authorities concerning sinking British steamer <hi rend="italic"
                            >Harpalyce</hi>, an English steamer with one funnel and four masts
                        proceeding towards England on morning April 10, namely, at time when <hi
                            rend="italic">Harpalyce</hi> is said to have gone down, was sunk in war
                        zone between British and Dutch coasts. This steamer did not however carry
                        markings of Belgian Relief Commission. It is not known whether this vessel
                        was the <hi rend="italic">Harpalyce</hi>. Accordingly the markings of relief
                        commission have not been disregarded.</p>
                </quote>
                <p>Your 2046, 5th. Furnish commission with copy note from <persName
                        corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward Grey</persName> referred to. Department not in
                    position to discuss matter with German and British Governments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
